Part two — operations.

The operations in this half apply uniformly across list, vector, set, the values of a map, array, and even string, which behaves like an indexed sequence of characters for these purposes. The payoff is that you learn them once and they work everywhere.

To make the examples concrete, picture a small set of demo data — a list of bank transactions. Each transaction is a small record with an id, a category, an amount, and a status. The list holds seven transactions across a few categories — some groceries, some fuel, some dining — with a mix of approved and declined statuses. We will run the operations against that list so each method has something realistic to chew on.

The mental model for this whole half is derive, do not mutate. Every operation here takes a collection and returns a new one — it never changes the original in place. You chain them together — filter, then map, then group — and each step hands a fresh collection to the next. That is the same model Spark uses at scale, so the habits you build here carry straight over.
